highly readable account based on extensive fieldwork among Mexican migrants and their American neighbors, Debra Lattanzi Shutika explores the issues of belonging and displacement that are central concerns for residents in communities that have become new destinations for Mexican settlement. Beyond the Borderlands also completes the circle of migration by following migrant families as they return to their hometown in Mexico, providing an illuminating perspective of the tenuous lives of Mexicans residing in, but not fully part of, two worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMexican AmericansxCultural assimilationzPennsylvaniazKennett Square. 0aMexican AmericanszPennsylvaniazKennett SquarexEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aborderlands.  acivic.  acultural anthropology.  ademographic studies.  adisplacement.  aethnic diversity.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  afarming village.  afieldwork.  ahispanic americans.  aimmigrant experience.  ainternational.  akennett square.  amexican americans.  amexican families.  amexican immigrants.  amexican settlement.  amexico.  amigrants.  aminority groups.  amodern world.  anonfiction.  apennsylvania.  asmall towns.  asuburbs.  aunited states.  aus borders.  aus immigration policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026959040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095023840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950238423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520950238/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY